"# Chapter 10 — The training loop

Everything the last four chapters set up gets used here. Forward
pass, loss, backward pass, parameter update. Do that many times on
many examples. That is training. Change the data, change the
architecture, change the loss, but the loop shape is the same
whether you are fitting a line or training GPT-4.

## The loop, in words

```
initialize parameters (randomly)
repeat many times:
  pick some examples
  forward: compute predictions from current parameters
  loss: compute how wrong the predictions are
  backward: compute the gradient of the loss with respect to every parameter
  update: parameter := parameter - learning_rate * gradient
stop when the loss is small enough (or you run out of time)
```

Every trained model in the world went through this loop. Big models
have more data, more parameters, and more sophisticated update rules
(Adam, AdamW), but the loop is exactly this shape.

## Problem 1 — Train a single neuron to fit y = 2x + 1

We did this in chapter 6 with finite-difference gradients. Now let's
do it with analytic backprop. Same result, faster, cleaner.

```
;; Data: pairs (x, y) where y = 2x + 1 with a little noise
(define data
  (list (cons -2.0 -3.0)
        (cons -1.0 -1.0)
        (cons  0.0  1.0)
        (cons  1.0  3.0)
        (cons  2.0  5.0)))

;; Model: y_pred = w*x + b
;; Loss: (y_pred - y_true)^2

(define (train-step w b lr example)
  (define x (car example))
  (define y-true (cdr example))
  (define y-pred (+ (* w x) b))
  ;; Backprop:
  (define dL-dy (* 2 (- y-pred y-true)))
  (define dL-dw (* dL-dy x))
  (define dL-db dL-dy)
  ;; Update:
  (list (- w (* lr dL-dw))
        (- b (* lr dL-db))))

(define (train-epoch w b lr data)
  (fold (lambda (example params)
          (train-step (car params) (cadr params) lr example))
        (list w b)
        data))

(define (mean-loss w b data)
  (define (sq p)
    (let ((y-pred (+ (* w (car p)) b))
          (y-true (cdr p)))
      (* (- y-pred y-true) (- y-pred y-true))))
  (/ (reduce + 0 (map sq data)) (length data)))

(define final
  (let loop ((w 0.0) (b 0.0) (epoch 0))
    (if (> epoch 200)
        (list w b (mean-loss w b data))
        (let ((next (train-epoch w b 0.05 data)))
          (loop (car next) (cadr next) (+ epoch 1))))))

(display final)
;; => approximately (2.0 1.0 ~0)
```

The neuron converged. Starting from `w=0, b=0`, after 200 epochs
(passes through the data), the parameters are essentially the true
`w=2, b=1` and the loss is essentially zero.

Read the code:

- `train-step` takes one example, computes gradients, updates.
- `train-epoch` folds `train-step` over the whole data list.
- The outer loop runs 200 epochs.
- `mean-loss` at the end tells us how well we did.

## Problem 2 — Batching

In problem 1 we updated after every example (called stochastic
gradient descent, or SGD). The gradient from one example is noisy.
Averaging gradients over a batch of examples smooths the noise.

Batch gradient descent:

```
(define (batch-gradient w b batch)
  (define n (length batch))
  (define (grads example)
    (let ((x (car example)) (y-true (cdr example)))
      (let ((y-pred (+ (* w x) b)))
        (let ((dL-dy (* 2 (- y-pred y-true))))
          (list (* dL-dy x) dL-dy)))))
  (define all (map grads batch))
  (define sum-dw (reduce + 0 (map car all)))
  (define sum-db (reduce + 0 (map cadr all)))
  (list (/ sum-dw n) (/ sum-db n)))

(define (batch-train w b lr batch)
  (define g (batch-gradient w b batch))
  (list (- w (* lr (car g)))
        (- b (* lr (cadr g)))))

(define data
  (list (cons -2.0 -3.0) (cons -1.0 -1.0)
        (cons  0.0  1.0) (cons  1.0  3.0) (cons 2.0 5.0)))

(define result
  (let loop ((w 0.0) (b 0.0) (n 0))
    (if (> n 500)
        (list w b)
        (let ((next (batch-train w b 0.1 data)))
          (loop (car next) (cadr next) (+ n 1))))))

(display result)
;; => approximately (2.0 1.0)
```

Same answer as SGD but the loss curve is smoother. In practice
mini-batches (10-256 examples) balance smoothness against speed.

## Problem 3 — Training a two-layer network on non-linear data

Now let's train the multi-layer perceptron from chapter 8. Target:
fit `y = x^2` on some data points. A linear model cannot do this.
A network with ReLU and a hidden layer can.

```
(define (relu x) (if (> x 0) x 0))
(define (relu-grad u) (if (> u 0) 1 0))

;; Two-layer network: 1 input, H hidden, 1 output
(define H 8)

;; Random initialization
(define (init-vec dim)
  (map (lambda (_) (- (* (random) 0.5) 0.25)) (iota dim)))

(define W1 (map (lambda (_) (init-vec 1)) (iota H)))    ;; H x 1
(define b1 (init-vec H))
(define W2 (list (init-vec H)))                          ;; 1 x H
(define b2 (init-vec 1))

;; Forward pass: returns (u1, h, y)
(define (forward W1 b1 W2 b2 x)
  (define u1 (map (lambda (row bi) (+ (vec/dot (vec/make row) (listx))) bi))
                  W1 b1))
  (define h  (map relu u1))
  (define y  (+ (vec/dot (vec/make (car W2)) (vec/make h)) (car b2)))
  (list u1 h y))

;; Backward: computes gradients for all parameters
(define (backward W1 b1 W2 b2 x y-true)
  (define fwd (forward W1 b1 W2 b2 x))
  (define u1 (car fwd))
  (define h  (cadr fwd))
  (define y  (caddr fwd))
  (define dL-dy (* 2 (- y y-true)))
  ;; y = W2·h + b2  -> dL/dW2[i] = dL-dy * h[i], dL/db2 = dL-dy
  (define dL-dW2 (list (map (lambda (hi) (* dL-dy hi)) h)))
  (define dL-db2 (list dL-dy))
  (define dL-dh (map (lambda (w2i) (* dL-dy w2i)) (car W2)))
  ;; h = relu(u1)  -> dL/du1[i] = dL-dh[i] * relu'(u1[i])
  (define dL-du1 (map (lambda (dh u) (* dh (relu-grad u))) dL-dh u1))
  ;; u1 = W1·x + b1 (each u1[i] = W1[i][0]*x + b1[i])
  (define dL-dW1 (map (lambda (du) (list (* du x))) dL-du1))
  (define dL-db1 dL-du1)
  (list dL-dW1 dL-db1 dL-dW2 dL-db2))

;; Update
(define (vec-update v grads lr)
  (map (lambda (vi gi) (- vi (* lr gi))) v grads))

(define (row-update rows grads lr)
  (map (lambda (r g) (vec-update r g lr)) rows grads))

;; Data
(define data
  (map (lambda (i)
         (let ((x (/ (- i 5) 2.5)))
           (cons x (* x x))))
       (iota 11)))
;; x from -2 to 2 in steps of 0.4, y = x^2

;; Training loop
(define lr 0.03)

(let loop ((W1 W1) (b1 b1) (W2 W2) (b2 b2) (epoch 0))
  (if (> epoch 3000)
      (begin
        (display \"final loss: \")
        (display
          (/ (reduce +
                     0
                     (map (lambda (p)
                            (let ((y (caddr (forward W1 b1 W2 b2 (car p)))))
                              (* (- y (cdr p)) (- y (cdr p)))))
                          data))
             (length data)))
        (newline))
      (let inner ((rem data) (W1 W1) (b1 b1) (W2 W2) (b2 b2))
        (if (null? rem)
            (loop W1 b1 W2 b2 (+ epoch 1))
            (let* ((example (car rem))
                   (grads (backward W1 b1 W2 b2 (car example) (cdr example)))
                   (dW1 (car grads))
                   (db1 (cadr grads))
                   (dW2 (caddr grads))
                   (db2 (cadddr grads)))
              (inner (cdr rem)
                     (row-update W1 dW1 lr)
                     (vec-update b1 db1 lr)
                     (row-update W2 dW2 lr)
                     (vec-update b2 db2 lr)))))))
;; final loss: something small (< 0.05 typically, depending on random init)
```

The network learned to approximate `y = x^2` on the training data.
The ReLU units bent the input space; the output layer summed them into
a curve. This is the smallest interesting neural network training in
Motoi Scheme.

Read the code carefully. It has all the pieces: forward pass, loss,
backward pass with chain rule, and parameter update. Nothing else.
Everything else in this book is more of the same, arranged
differently.

## Problem 4 — Overfitting

If you train a large network on a small dataset, it may memorize the
training examples rather than learning the underlying pattern. The
training loss goes to zero. The loss on held-out (test) data is
large. That is overfitting.

```
;; If your training data has 5 points and your network has 50
;; parameters, the network has enough capacity to hit every training
;; point exactly and do nothing sensible in between.
```

The fix: more data, or a smaller model, or regularization (a penalty
in the loss that discourages large parameters), or dropout (randomly
zeroing hidden units during training). Real ML is largely about
managing this trade-off.

For a language model, overfitting means memorizing the training
corpus rather than learning language patterns. Big models trained
on huge corpora have a hard time overfitting because there is too
much data to memorize. Small models on small corpora overfit like
mad.

## Problem 5 — When to stop

Training does not stop 'automatically.' You choose when. Two
strategies.

**Fixed number of epochs.** Train for a preset number of passes over
the data. Simple, predictable.

**Early stopping.** Keep a held-out validation set. Train and track
loss on the validation set. When the validation loss stops decreasing
(or starts increasing), stop. That is the moment the model started
to overfit.

Modern practice is early stopping with a patience of a few epochs:
stop after N consecutive epochs of no validation improvement.

## Capstone — Training loop template

A complete training loop as a template you can reuse. Not for any
particular model — a scaffold.

```
;; Given:
;;   init-params  -> parameters
;;   forward params x -> prediction
;;   loss params batch -> scalar
;;   backward params batch -> gradient
;;   update params gradient lr -> new params
(define (train init-params forward loss backward update data lr epochs)
  (let loop ((params init-params) (epoch 0))
    (if (>= epoch epochs)
        params
        (let ((g (backward params data)))
          (let ((new-params (update params g lr)))
            (when (= (modulo epoch 100) 0)
              (display \"epoch \") (display epoch)
              (display \" loss \") (display (loss new-params data))
              (newline))
            (loop new-params (+ epoch 1)))))))
```

This shape works for any model. Change `forward`, `backward`, and
`update` to match the architecture. The loop shell is invariant.

## Why this matters

You now know how to train. From random weights, through many small
updates, to a model that fits data. This is the mechanism that
produces every trained model in the world. Chapters 11-15 build the
architecture of a language model. Chapter 16 trains it with the loop
you just learned.

## What's next

Chapter 11 is where the language part of language models begins. We
have to turn words into vectors. That is what tokens and embeddings
are for. Once we have vectors, all the machinery from chapters 2-10
applies directly.
")
